kevalin 11-Dec-21 03:34 AM
@PrimalNick sent a few idea that find valuable. Some big things to be looking out for that’ll help inform Phase 3 and 4 are: - what viral loops can we start baking in to the product (i.e. add the short tags to your twitter name to get priviledges in this server, etc)? - what does a successful community look like (are there ways to tangibly track that and add it to the site to guide the leaderboard?)(i.e. community progress, etc)? - how do we make this a continuous game (rather than one winner, we make it a constant competition)(i.e. CoinMarketCap for DAOs)? - how do we better guide people to projects that are actually doing well, not just hyped up (i.e. standardizing and opening the data streams to the community for different metrics like retention, daily active users, etc)? - how do we simplify the experience for the community, making it more enticing to start a project (i.e. Kevs idea for one click to DAO and discord formation, etc)? Please use these as guiding ideas!

LZRS 11-Dec-21 07:06 AM
I merged the sign in with discord code. Ideally, somebody can finish this because I may not have much time this weekend. If no one else does it, I can do it... but I wanted to share this in the interest of time. Here is what needs to be done: 1. We need to implement voting. In order to do this, we want to create an authenticated route that takes the email address of the user and adds it to the votes array. This would be the mongo document schema: https://discord.com/channels/916751469678579784/918664946332598323/919108633101479956 We should be sure not to add the same vote twice https://discord.com/channels/916751469678579784/918664946332598323/919116594813210664 Also see this thread for more implementation discussion: https://discord.com/channels/916751469678579784/918664946332598323/919097107879702580 Here is relevant next-auth documentation: https://next-auth.js.org/getting-started/client#getsession 2. We need a sign out button. This is really easy, it just needs to say "Sign Out" instead of "Connect Discord" and you can use the signOut function build into next-auth: https://next-auth.js.org/getting-started/client#signout 3. We need to add the NEXTAUTH_URL environment variable (https://next-auth.js.org/v3/configuration/options#environment-variables) and a secret for the configuration (https://next-auth.js.org/v3/configuration/options#secret)

LZRS
I merged the sign in with discord code. Ideally, somebody can finish this because I may not have much time this weekend. If no one else does it, I can do it... but I wanted to share this in the interest of time. Here is what needs to be done: 1. We need to implement voting. In order to do this, we want to create an authenticated route that takes the email address of the user and adds it to the votes array. This would be the mongo document schema: https://discord.com/channels/916751469678579784/918664946332598323/919108633101479956 We should be sure not to add the same vote twice https://discord.com/channels/916751469678579784/918664946332598323/919116594813210664 Also see this thread for more implementation discussion: https://discord.com/channels/916751469678579784/918664946332598323/919097107879702580 Here is relevant next-auth documentation: https://next-auth.js.org/getting-started/client#getsession 2. We need a sign out button. This is really easy, it just needs to say "Sign Out" instead of "Connect Discord" and you can use the signOut function build into next-auth: https://next-auth.js.org/getting-started/client#signout 3. We need to add the NEXTAUTH_URL environment variable (https://next-auth.js.org/v3/configuration/options#environment-variables) and a secret for the configuration (https://next-auth.js.org/v3/configuration/options#secret)

LZRS
I merged the sign in with discord code. Ideally, somebody can finish this because I may not have much time this weekend. If no one else does it, I can do it... but I wanted to share this in the interest of time. Here is what needs to be done: 1. We need to implement voting. In order to do this, we want to create an authenticated route that takes the email address of the user and adds it to the votes array. This would be the mongo document schema: https://discord.com/channels/916751469678579784/918664946332598323/919108633101479956 We should be sure not to add the same vote twice https://discord.com/channels/916751469678579784/918664946332598323/919116594813210664 Also see this thread for more implementation discussion: https://discord.com/channels/916751469678579784/918664946332598323/919097107879702580 Here is relevant next-auth documentation: https://next-auth.js.org/getting-started/client#getsession 2. We need a sign out button. This is really easy, it just needs to say "Sign Out" instead of "Connect Discord" and you can use the signOut function build into next-auth: https://next-auth.js.org/getting-started/client#signout 3. We need to add the NEXTAUTH_URL environment variable (https://next-auth.js.org/v3/configuration/options#environment-variables) and a secret for the configuration (https://next-auth.js.org/v3/configuration/options#secret)
LZRS 12-Dec-21 04:33 AM
I’ve completed 1 just now. @boshd completed 2. Still need to do 3.
Also now that votes are implemented, we need to aggregate the vote totals and sort queries. It would also be good to have pagination

kevalin 22-Dec-21 01:33 PM
I'd like to clarify the bounty market to the core pods. Bounty markets are for short-term contributors. It's more of mercenary tasks. For longer-term contributors like what the core pods do now, we have a different approach. The core team is in the process of spinning up pods that have resources to pay pod members. The core pods are similar to what these future pods will do. The future pods will dedicate more time and be able to quite fast. Closer to salaries than bounties. See more info on Hyperscale's structure here: https://hyperscale.notion.site/Structure-8b25c68113694dd999d7e5f7aa704bad cc: @Core-Dev @Core-Design (edited)

Ubiubi2018 26-Dec-21 10:58 AM
I indeed think that fake voting is inevitable as soon as monetary incentives are involved. If not now, than next round.
Better think about some form of sybil-resistant identity beyond sms-verification to defend some meaningful voting.
Though even 'stronger' KYC is not necessarily reliable, once high monetary incentives are involved. After several years of scammy exchanges and ICOs requesting pictures of passports and IDs, the black market for such kind of KYC data should be saturated? (edited)
Not meant to be destructive comment.
There are several experiments/solutions for proof of Person/ proof of human out there . It will take more time to build something meaningful, but it is not impossible. The DAO-Hype will only be successful once we have precondition of more sybil-resistant identity on blockchain.
Meanwhile i would rather trust only DAOs where participants somehow constituted with a meeting in real life. Some real life web of trust. Or you add some level of anonymous sybil resistance like idenanetwork, though it will require much more time and work to make it feasable
Just please dont rely only on social handles, email, sms... has failed many times before over the years to trust something like that

tom 29-Dec-21 10:02 PM
fyi: @pawel and I have looked into structured logging for the race and it turns out that Vercel and the serverless mode of execution is slightly limiting in this regard. https://github.com/hyper-scale/race/pull/140 demonstrates a working setup with Datadog, but given that Vercel does not yet support Datadog APM, the outcome is somewhat limited to just being a log aggregator. Imho, Datadog is a bit too complex to justify for if that’s the only thing we get from it. We think about closing this PR for now and get back to it once we switch execution environment or Vercel adds support for APM.

pawel 30-Dec-21 06:13 PM
I propose that core-dev as a team decides about items I raised earlier. Including removal from the core-dev e.g. if someone is not active for longer. Additionally all GitHub configuration, including membership and rights should be in GitHub repo. Based on GitHub membership configuration discord badges are assigned so all is transparent. We have calls every 2 weeks about general technical items and decide who can join the core and who should leave (based on objective stuff like PRs/reviews/merges/helpfulness on discord/coordination with other teams etc). When we start new project/hackathoon/iteration/whatever, the team self-organises in order to achieve business goals. Team has full decision power about technology stack. Team chooses its representative/leader (if needed) (edited)
3
3
OmnistratMatt 30-Dec-21 06:14 PM
Folks, I've been monitoring convos throughout this server for the last couple of days. There are many decisions still to be made and problems to solve. Unfortunately, there is no shortage of opinions and conversations happening with little insight into who knows their stuff and who doesn't. Makes for a tough environment when you're just starting out. I feel for Kevalin as he has so much on his shoulders as the defacto leader trying to manage it all. Luckily, there are contributors rising to the top to help (referring to you folks here). Here is something to think about. Many web3 projects start off with a traditional startup setup, i.e., a core team of paid employees, and then gradually transitions to decentralized once the project is more stable. Now that a core team can be fielded, its an option to have this core group get the mvp out. Bring questions, problems, and challenges to the community to help solve but control the process. Yes, it isn't very DAO-like now but it will get there. Right now some critical decisions have too many cooks in the kitchen. This can weaken the project. This project is worthwhile and has amazing traction out of the gate but the possibility still exists that it implodes on itself. Again, just a thought. You folks know what you're doing and I'm sure you'll work things out.

BenJ 30-Dec-21 08:22 PM
My 2 cents. I think the DAO has tried to do too much too soon, certainly from a d decentralised POV. The DAO race was a great idea in principle, but clearly had / has pitfalls. Whilst I’m delighted to be involved, Sam’s initial tweet was ‘some sort of web3 investment thing’ - I feel investments would have already been made if it was a simple ‘pitch’ put in front of Sam and a few handful of others. Not very web3, I realise, but much like @OmnistratMatt says, it could have iteratively progressed from there. This is not at all to say ‘we should have done it differently’, (of course we couldn’t have and I certainly didn’t know any better) but it’s to learn from this going forwards. I think identifying a core leadership team, that discusses everything and make all decisions in public (but without external input) would help with the speed of execution. Props to everyone so far who’s contributed, and I hope to get more stuck in going forwards.
